	abstract = {Highly accurate measurements of the entropic coefficient of lithium-ion batteries (LIBs) over a wide state-of-charge (SoC) range are essential for optimizing the thermal management systems used to maintain battery temperature within an appropriate level, and thereby limit the aging process and avoid thermal runaway, which can lead to fire or explosions. This is usually accomplished by the potentiometric method. However, the high time consumption of this method greatly limits its usefulness in commercial settings. The present work addresses this issue by proposing a fast and precise method to determine the entropic coefficients of LIBs based on frequency-domain analysis employing a standard square wave current with a DC offset as input. The entropic coefficient is then obtained at each SoC level through Fourier transform according to the magnitudes of the fundamental frequency components of the heat generation rate and current. The measurement error introduced by the DC offset and internal resistance is analyzed in this paper. The continuous entropic coefficient profile of a commercial LiFePO4/Graphite prismatic cell is measured and the results are compared with those obtained from the potentiometric method. The analysis demonstrates that employing the average of the entropic coefficient profiles obtained under charging and discharging conditions is an effective means of eliminating the error introduced by the DC offset current and the effect of hysteresis. As a result, the proposed method not only obtains a continuous entropic coefficient profile that agrees well with the discrete values obtained using the potentiometric method, but does so in 1/10 of the time. Hence, the proposed method has the potential for use in on-board battery diagnostics applications.},
